Here&#39;s a stream/collector-based solution. It turns maps into streams of entries, concatenates them and then collects into a map, using entry keys as keys and summing values as `int`s.

		Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; HM1 = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
		Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; HM2 = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
		HM1.put(&quot;foo&quot;, 1);
		HM1.put(&quot;bar&quot;, 1);

		HM2.put(&quot;foo&quot;, 1);
		HM2.put(&quot;main&quot;, 1);
		
		Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; result = Stream
			.concat(HM1.entrySet().stream(), HM2.entrySet().stream())
			.collect(
					Collectors.groupingBy(
							Map.Entry::getKey,
							Collectors.summingInt(Map.Entry::getValue)));

Another way to accomplish this is by using the [toMap Collector][1], which is defined to take a merge function:
```Java
var hm1 = new HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt;();
hm1.put(&quot;foo&quot;,1);
hm1.put(&quot;bar&quot;,2);
var hm2 = new HashMap&lt;String, Integer&gt;();
hm2.put(&quot;foo&quot;,4);
hm2.put(&quot;baz&quot;,8);
var v = Stream.of(hm1, hm2)
    .map(Map::entrySet)
    .flatMap(Set::stream)
    .collect(
        Collectors.toMap(
            Map.Entry::getKey,   // key mapper
            Map.Entry::getValue, // value mapper
            Integer::sum         // merge function
        )
    );
System.out.println(v);
```
